{
  "query": "To restore peatlands afforested for commercial forestry, how does simply cutting the trees compare to cutting trees and also rewetting the peat?",
  "relevant_summary": "Cutting/removing/thinning forest plantations alone increased cover of some herb species (e.g., cottongrasses and sedges) in bogs and fens, reduced forest\u2011characteristic mosses, and showed mixed responses for Sphagnum, including decreases over three years in a drained rich fen [1731]. Cutting/removing/thinning forest plantations combined with rewetting led to changes in overall plant community composition away from drained, forested states; increased abundance of wetland\u2011characteristic plants; increased cover of Sphagnum in some studies (with others reporting no or mixed effects); reduced non\u2011Sphagnum or forest\u2011characteristic mosses; increased cover of at least some herb groups; increased ground vegetation height in one bog; reduced numbers of tall trees for 1\u20133 years; and increased plant species richness in rich fens (with no effect on total richness/diversity in some fens) [1732].",
